   <methods>
      <methodStep>
         <description>
  <para><emphasis>This section contains specific methods for this dataset.</emphasis></para>
  <para> * LANDCOVER CLASS AGGREGATION DATA </para>
  <para>To gauge the effect of spatial scale and aggregation on remotely-sensed land cover classifications across such locally heterogeneous and patchy ecosystems as barrier islands, data was collected inside and outside each plot in the four cardinal directions at set distances outward from plot center (0, 7.5, 15, 30, and 60 m) as to what the dominant woody and herbaceous canopy components were as well as the woody and herbaceous canopy heights. The dominant two species in terms of overhead tree/shrub canopy (in a subjective 2-3m radius zone) and herbaceous canopy (1 m radius) around the collection point was recorded as well as the average height of the primary dominant. The cover types were classified as being one of thirteen types: 1) low salt marsh, 2) upper salt marsh, 3) salt hay meadow [brackish-fresh marsh dominated by Spartina patens and/or Distichlis spicata], 4)reedy or scrub marsh [dominated by Phragmites, Typha, Juncus, or Iva], 5) evergreen conifer forest, 6) evergreen broadleaf forest, 7) deciduous broadleaf forest, 8) shrubland [mostly Myrica and/or Baccharis with varying amounts of Smilax briers], 9) beach/dune exposed sparsely vegetated sand, 10) open water, 11) upland or dune grassland, 12) mixed forest types, or 14) mudflat [with or without wrack]. The nine samples from within the permanent plot (0, 7.5, and 15 m distances) can be compared to the stem map of nearby trees and shrubs of different sizes to work out a more quantified description of just what constituted each forest or shrubland type.</para>
         </description>
      </methodStep>
   </methods>
